WEBVTT

00:00.917 --> 00:02.877
NARRATOR:
<i>Previously on </i>Chesapeake Shores:

00:03.044 --> 00:04.629
You've been running it in absentia.

00:04.796 --> 00:08.174
-From now on, we do it my way.
-Contracts are open for interpretation.

00:08.341 --> 00:11.511
I will not resign.
You didn't fire me because you can't.

00:11.678 --> 00:14.514
U.S. Fish and Wildlife will be
filing suit against you next week.

00:14.681 --> 00:16.391
You have a new client,
she requested you.

00:16.850 --> 00:18.601
You might know her as Ms. Marvel.

00:18.768 --> 00:20.895
What would you say
if I took a job in Philadelphia?

00:21.062 --> 00:23.356
-What?
-You gave me the manuscript first.

00:23.523 --> 00:29.320
But I can't give you my blessings on it.
Not before you show it to your mother.

00:32.490 --> 00:34.492
[♪♪♪]

00:35.618 --> 00:40.123
Don't worry. Even if the building inspector
finds something, it's not a big deal.

00:40.290 --> 00:44.169
I know, I know. It's no big deal at all.
It's a small deal.

00:44.669 --> 00:46.921
Authority figures make me nervous.
I'm sorry.

00:47.088 --> 00:49.007
Have you noticed frass
anywhere in the house?

00:49.174 --> 00:51.384
I might have missed the frass.

00:51.551 --> 00:54.262
I don't know what frass is.
Is frass good or is frass bad?

00:54.429 --> 00:56.765
-Is something wrong?
-It looks like you have termites.

00:57.223 --> 00:58.725
Termites?

00:58.892 --> 01:00.018
How bad?

01:00.185 --> 01:03.063
It's difficult to know until we bring in
a termite thermographer.

01:03.229 --> 01:05.356
-To...?
-To assess the infestation.

01:06.608 --> 01:08.818
I'm sorry, but an inn once quoted...

01:08.985 --> 01:11.071
...by the legendary travel writer
Kenneth Shane...

01:11.237 --> 01:14.532
...as being a "home away from home"
would not have infestations.

01:14.699 --> 01:18.036
Would scones this delicious
be made at an infested inn?

01:23.333 --> 01:26.294
Okay, well, termites aren't so bad, right?

01:26.461 --> 01:27.796
We can deal with termites.

01:27.962 --> 01:30.423
Yeah, no problem. Knock on wood.

01:32.091 --> 01:34.594
On second thought,
maybe not such a good idea.

01:40.642 --> 01:43.311
<i>♪ Plane ticket already paid ♪</i>

01:43.520 --> 01:46.147
<i>♪ I'm gone</i>
<i>But it don't mean nothing ♪</i>

01:46.314 --> 01:50.401
<i>♪ I'm close even though I'm far away ♪</i>

01:52.195 --> 01:54.781
<i>♪ That's how I remember you ♪</i>

01:54.989 --> 01:57.617
<i>♪ Stuck here on the red-eye special ♪</i>

01:57.784 --> 02:02.205
<i>♪ I can't wait to see you again ♪</i>

02:03.540 --> 02:07.877
<i>♪ So don't think of me</i>
<i>Not being around ♪</i>

02:09.587 --> 02:15.343
<i>♪ Just listen for the sweet, sweet sound</i>
<i>Of the taxi pulling up the driveway ♪</i>

02:15.510 --> 02:18.513
<i>♪ I'm coming home soon ♪</i>

02:21.641 --> 02:24.561
<i>♪ I'm coming home soon ♪</i>

02:25.019 --> 02:27.313
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪</i>

02:27.689 --> 02:30.316
<i>♪ Da-da-da-da ♪</i> <i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪</i>

02:34.070 --> 02:36.030
<i>♪ Da-da-da ♪</i>

02:36.573 --> 02:39.534
<i>♪ Da-da, da-da-da ♪♪</i>

02:41.911 --> 02:43.913
[♪♪♪]

02:45.748 --> 02:48.459
Oh! It's our honored guest.

02:48.626 --> 02:50.044
[HOWLS]

02:50.712 --> 02:52.714
That's the way it should be
when I enter a room.

02:53.548 --> 02:57.176
Uh, except that was for me,
and graduation's really not a big deal.

02:57.343 --> 03:00.388
Of course, it is, Kevin. Congratulations.
It's time for the big ceremony.

03:00.555 --> 03:03.182
I already told you,
there's not gonna-- Oh, forget it.

03:03.349 --> 03:05.268
Nell and I are throwing a party
to celebrate.

03:05.435 --> 03:06.644
NELL: Yes.
MEGAN: Everybody in?

03:06.811 --> 03:08.813
-Yeah.
-Great. Yes.

03:09.439 --> 03:10.857
Oh, early start, huh?

03:11.024 --> 03:13.902
Yes, I have an early-morning meeting
with Terri Ingram.

03:14.068 --> 03:15.612
-Isn't that Ms. Marvel?
-Mm-hm.

03:15.778 --> 03:17.989
-Why?
-She has work for the firm...

03:18.156 --> 03:19.824
...and she has requested me.

03:19.991 --> 03:21.492
Well, how do you feel about that?

03:21.659 --> 03:24.787
It's fine. She's perfect,
why would perfect bother me?

03:25.204 --> 03:26.289
Bye.

03:26.456 --> 03:27.832
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

03:27.999 --> 03:30.501
Huh. If anybody wants
to find me this afternoon...

03:30.668 --> 03:32.670
...I'll be at Sally's,
where Danielle Clayman...

03:32.837 --> 03:34.297
...is treating me to lunch.

03:34.464 --> 03:35.673
Really?

03:35.840 --> 03:39.093
I think she just wants to yell at me
for destroying her case.

03:39.260 --> 03:40.803
Well, don't be too smug.

03:40.970 --> 03:43.056
Well, Gran, he who laughs last....

03:43.223 --> 03:45.266
-Laughs alone?
-Ha-ha-ha.

03:45.433 --> 03:47.435
That's a good point. See you.

03:47.602 --> 03:49.896
Kevin, are you free this afternoon?

03:50.063 --> 03:52.523
I'm meeting Sarah this morning.
We can meet after.

03:52.690 --> 03:55.109
-Good.
-All right. Bye.

03:55.276 --> 03:56.819
Love you.

03:56.986 --> 03:58.821
[CLEARS THROAT]

03:58.988 --> 04:01.741
[♪♪♪]

04:03.534 --> 04:09.040
Uh, you know, I think I need
to really go get some more decorations...

04:09.207 --> 04:15.505
...for the party,
so if you ladies will just excuse me.

04:15.672 --> 04:17.215
Bye, Gran.

04:23.012 --> 04:25.306
Mom, is something wrong?

04:28.768 --> 04:30.853
I read your book.

04:31.271 --> 04:32.897
And?

04:33.606 --> 04:34.941
[DOOR SLAMS]

04:39.779 --> 04:41.197
[SIGHS]

04:44.367 --> 04:47.412
So you'll see the new schedule
with employee workflow and productivity.

04:47.578 --> 04:49.622
And menu items
have been standardized.

04:49.789 --> 04:51.916
Good. How often
will we be getting these reports?

04:52.083 --> 04:55.253
Nightly, and bookkeeping will be
accessible with 256-bit...

04:55.420 --> 04:56.838
...double-key protection.

04:57.005 --> 04:58.298
Good, good.

04:58.464 --> 05:01.801
-How's it all look to you?
-Uh, not-- Not great.

05:02.593 --> 05:04.804
You cut the afternoon hours in half.

05:05.471 --> 05:07.140
They aren't profitable.

05:07.307 --> 05:10.310
But the lunch shift makes the Bridge
a place where people can come...

05:10.476 --> 05:13.313
...and de-stress from work,
listen to some great country music.

05:13.479 --> 05:18.067
And it taxes staffing
and scheduling and vendor accessibility.

05:18.234 --> 05:20.528
I'm sure there's room for compromise.

05:20.695 --> 05:23.906
With all due respect, Chris has no idea
what the Bridge is about.

05:24.073 --> 05:27.285
This is a country-music venue,
first and foremost.

05:27.452 --> 05:30.288
Look, I know you do the music thing here.

05:30.455 --> 05:34.500
And I appreciate your knowledge,
but I've gone over your receipts...

05:34.667 --> 05:38.296
...and the bands you bring in
are expensive and don't generate sales.

05:38.463 --> 05:41.507
The acts you're booking,
they're not right for the club.

05:41.674 --> 05:44.010
They all track well
in similar small-town venues.

05:44.177 --> 05:46.512
Increasing revenue
during performances.

05:46.679 --> 05:48.181
Have you actually listened to them?

05:48.347 --> 05:51.601
I know about half these bands,
and they're terrible.

05:52.101 --> 05:55.313
It's the kind of music
you'd listen to in a Waffle House.

05:55.480 --> 05:57.940
Look, Chris is just giving us
a starting point.

05:58.649 --> 06:01.778
I need someone I can trust
running the business of this club.

06:02.320 --> 06:06.491
Yeah, well, having someone I can trust
might be a good place to start too.

06:06.657 --> 06:08.951
[♪♪♪]

06:12.413 --> 06:14.791
SARAH:
Congratulations, paramedic.

06:15.166 --> 06:16.501
So do you feel any different?

06:16.667 --> 06:21.631
Well, seeing how I just finished yesterday,
not particularly.

06:21.798 --> 06:23.716
Hey, did you take the New York Fire job?

06:25.468 --> 06:27.428
Not yet.

06:28.763 --> 06:30.556
I got my start date for Philly.

06:31.974 --> 06:34.185
It's a week from tomorrow.

06:34.352 --> 06:36.187
[♪♪♪]

06:37.897 --> 06:39.315
So you're going?

06:40.316 --> 06:43.361
Yeah. Yeah, I guess so.

06:43.528 --> 06:46.405
And if you take New York,
it's not that far.

06:46.572 --> 06:47.615
Two hours.

06:47.782 --> 06:51.202
-We can take turns commuting.
-Yeah. We'll just have to organize
day shifts, night shifts...

06:55.957 --> 06:58.209
...schedules, vacations.

06:58.376 --> 07:00.128
Won't be that hard.

07:00.503 --> 07:03.089
No, no. Shouldn't be too hard.

07:05.133 --> 07:06.551
Well, congratulations.

07:09.846 --> 07:10.888
Yay.

07:19.605 --> 07:22.775
So Stewart &amp; Stuart want to buy
into your blog...

07:22.942 --> 07:24.652
...and expand the Ms. Marvel brand?

07:24.819 --> 07:27.405
Correct.
And we're well into negotiations.

07:28.156 --> 07:31.200
Wes wants me to do it, I want to do it...

07:31.367 --> 07:33.744
...but I thought
I should get a second opinion.

07:34.412 --> 07:37.039
That's a wise decision, Ms. Ingram.

07:37.498 --> 07:41.419
If you're looking for us to analyze
the numbers, there's no need.

07:41.586 --> 07:43.671
Hunter, Drew &amp; Associates
is an excellent firm.

07:44.130 --> 07:45.715
I know.

07:45.882 --> 07:48.050
But I don't want the numbers.

07:48.217 --> 07:50.970
To everyone in the world,
this is who I am.

07:51.137 --> 07:53.556
Ms. Marvel is me.

07:53.723 --> 07:56.976
I wanna make sure
I'm making the right decision.

07:57.143 --> 07:59.145
[♪♪♪]

08:03.107 --> 08:07.028
If you're waiting for an apology,
we may be here for a while.

08:07.195 --> 08:09.947
Are you kidding? You played me.

08:10.823 --> 08:14.160
-And I kind of enjoyed it.
-Ha-ha.

08:14.952 --> 08:17.747
However, our managing partner
wasn't so happy.

08:17.914 --> 08:21.667
He doesn't like to lose, especially
to a lawyer from the O'Brien Foundation.

08:21.834 --> 08:23.252
Ah.

08:23.753 --> 08:25.963
-You're not in trouble, are you?
-No.

08:26.130 --> 08:30.468
But I did have to spend a couple hours
explaining how and why it happened.

08:30.635 --> 08:32.762
Which is why I'm here. -You're still not getting an apology.
-Heh.

08:35.223 --> 08:36.599
Good.

08:36.933 --> 08:38.434
My firm wants to hire you.

08:38.601 --> 08:42.855
Well, you do know that I only work
for the good guys, right?

08:43.022 --> 08:45.399
The fish, the water, the plants.

08:45.566 --> 08:48.110
And you do know
that we work for both sides.

08:48.277 --> 08:50.071
Well, whoever's paying.

08:50.238 --> 08:53.616
In this case, it's a fishery that happens
to be next to an abandoned steel mill.

08:53.783 --> 08:54.867
Sparrow's Cove?

08:55.034 --> 08:56.285
Yeah. You know it?

08:56.452 --> 08:58.371
I came across it in my research.

08:58.538 --> 09:01.582
The fishery wants the area cleaned up.
And rightfully so.

09:01.749 --> 09:04.502
So you think
your firm could loan you out for a bit?

09:05.753 --> 09:08.005
We'd cover your hours and expenses.

09:09.215 --> 09:14.929
Yeah. I'd have to discuss it with Thomas,
but I think that can be arranged.

09:16.847 --> 09:18.516
So...

09:19.850 --> 09:21.435
...we're okay, though, right?

09:21.936 --> 09:24.272
Yeah. Yeah, of course.

09:25.106 --> 09:27.817
That is,
if your firm is picking up the check.

09:27.984 --> 09:29.235
-Oh, of course.
-Good.

09:29.402 --> 09:31.279
All right, then I'm gonna order dessert.

09:31.445 --> 09:32.905
-Get two.
-Ha-ha.

09:33.072 --> 09:35.074
-Will do. Sally!
-Heh-heh-heh.

09:37.994 --> 09:40.162
Well, if it isn't Captain Ahab.

09:40.329 --> 09:42.957
-I guess that makes you Ishmael.
-Heh-heh.

09:43.124 --> 09:44.667
Who else knows about this?

09:44.834 --> 09:47.712
Thomas, Connor, your mom,
and now you.

09:48.254 --> 09:50.506
-Saving the best for last, huh?
-Heh.

09:50.673 --> 09:52.800
-Come on aboard.
-Yeah.

09:53.509 --> 09:54.885
[MICK SIGHS]

09:58.055 --> 10:00.641
-So, what are your plans now?
-Uh....

10:00.808 --> 10:02.768
I don't know. I'm thinking N.Y.F.D.

10:02.935 --> 10:05.062
-Not too sure.
-Ah, New York's bravest.

10:05.229 --> 10:08.524
That's what they keep telling me.
But I don't know.

10:08.691 --> 10:10.401
I still haven't decided.

10:10.568 --> 10:13.863
That would put you and Sarah
about four hours apart.

10:14.030 --> 10:15.489
Actually, two.

10:15.656 --> 10:18.451
She's transferring
to the Philadelphia Fire Department.

10:18.993 --> 10:21.954
-To be closer to her family?
-Yeah.

10:23.331 --> 10:25.583
So, what's there to figure out?

10:28.085 --> 10:31.672
You think that there's just one person
out there for everyone?

10:32.590 --> 10:35.259
I don't know. Heh. Why?

10:35.426 --> 10:39.305
When I was with Georgia,
I wondered about it.

10:39.472 --> 10:42.975
Now that I'm with Sarah,
I kind of think it's true.

10:44.352 --> 10:48.022
-That's a nice feeling to have, isn't it?
-Yeah.

10:48.564 --> 10:50.691
That's what scares me
about letting her go.

10:52.568 --> 10:55.863
I don't suppose it'd help
if I told you it's all gonna work out.

10:56.030 --> 10:58.866
-Not really.
-Heh-heh-heh.

10:59.033 --> 11:00.993
Well, what I believe is that...

11:01.160 --> 11:03.621
...if you two want something
badly enough...

11:03.788 --> 11:05.790
...you'll make it happen. [♪♪♪]

11:09.835 --> 11:11.962
ABBY:
They'll start with the all-purpose cleaner.

11:12.129 --> 11:14.173
If that sells,
they'll move on to other products.

11:14.340 --> 11:15.466
That's what they say.

11:15.633 --> 11:17.802
And the all-purpose cleaner,
you developed?

11:17.968 --> 11:19.095
That was a long time ago.

11:19.261 --> 11:23.224
My first husband had just left,
and my daughter's skin broke out.

11:23.391 --> 11:25.768
And that's why you started the blog?

11:25.935 --> 11:28.729
I don't know.
I just felt like I had something to say...

11:28.896 --> 11:31.899
...to other single parents.
That we're all in the same boat.

11:32.066 --> 11:33.275
Hmm.

11:33.442 --> 11:38.948
Well, Caitlyn's allergic to everything,
and Wes and I have to be so careful, it's....

11:39.824 --> 11:41.700
But, of course, you know that.

11:41.867 --> 11:43.828
Heh. I do.

11:44.787 --> 11:47.206
And with the blog being as big as it is...

11:47.373 --> 11:50.000
...Stewart &amp; Stuart approached me
to license my name.

11:51.001 --> 11:53.379
They are a reputable company.

11:53.838 --> 11:56.298
And Wes suggested I come to you.

11:58.050 --> 12:00.428
I know this must be weird.

12:00.594 --> 12:05.015
But he said no one is as honest as you.

12:06.434 --> 12:09.562
So, what do you think?

12:09.728 --> 12:11.313
[♪♪♪]

12:11.480 --> 12:13.607
Honestly, I can't give you that yet.

12:13.774 --> 12:18.154
But this is your company...

12:19.280 --> 12:21.449
...and Ms. Marvel doesn't exist
without you.

12:25.453 --> 12:26.704
[SIGHS]

12:39.216 --> 12:40.759
Hi.

12:42.470 --> 12:47.600
Gran asked me to get some decorations
for the party, so I got this banner.

12:55.649 --> 12:56.692
Mom?

12:56.859 --> 12:58.486
[♪♪♪]

12:58.652 --> 13:00.946
You write beautifully, Bree.

13:04.992 --> 13:07.077
Okay. Um....

13:08.329 --> 13:10.915
Mom, the book isn't about the family.

13:13.959 --> 13:16.295
Okay, fine. Um....

13:16.712 --> 13:20.466
I didn't intend for it to be....

13:24.512 --> 13:28.891
If that's how you see me,
then you don't know me at all.

13:37.900 --> 13:39.652
[♪♪♪]

13:39.818 --> 13:43.322
Absolutely, the Abby Room
is available this weekend. Uh....

13:43.489 --> 13:44.657
Wonderful.

13:44.823 --> 13:46.659
It's perfect timing.

13:46.825 --> 13:48.953
Okay, great. We'll see you then.

13:49.119 --> 13:50.788
-Hi.
-I heard the news.

13:50.955 --> 13:53.165
-How bad is it?
-I don't know yet.

13:53.332 --> 13:56.252
Hoping we're not gonna have
to shut down.

13:56.418 --> 13:58.128
The infestation is worse than expected.

13:58.671 --> 14:00.256
-Hey, Mick.
-Hey, Michele.

14:00.422 --> 14:02.466
You think we're gonna have to tent?

14:02.925 --> 14:04.843
Unfortunately, there's nothing left to tent.

14:05.010 --> 14:08.639
The joists, trusses and support beams
have all been eaten away.

14:08.806 --> 14:10.808
-Oh, no.
-So, what are you saying?

14:11.308 --> 14:14.144
It's a miracle
the entire house hasn't collapsed.

14:15.437 --> 14:16.855
[SCOFFS]

14:17.356 --> 14:18.691
So how do I fix this?

14:19.108 --> 14:21.068
There's nothing left to fix.

14:21.235 --> 14:24.530
I'm sorry, it's pretty much a teardown.

14:24.697 --> 14:25.906
[GASPS]

14:29.159 --> 14:30.411
Um....

14:30.578 --> 14:33.998
Okay, a teardown isn't
that big a deal, right?

14:34.164 --> 14:37.042
I mean, we just have
to bulldoze the house...

14:37.209 --> 14:39.920
...and start over from nothing.

14:40.087 --> 14:41.505
It's no biggie.

14:41.672 --> 14:43.424
Oh, Jess, I'm so sorry.

14:44.133 --> 14:46.844
Dad, I can't lose the inn. I just can't.

14:47.970 --> 14:50.264
It's gonna be okay, sweetheart.

14:50.556 --> 14:52.433
Dad, I don't think it will this time.

14:53.767 --> 14:55.895
Dad, this was me.

14:56.061 --> 14:59.857
This was my chance
at being a better Jess.

15:00.399 --> 15:04.987
This was my chance at being successful
like everyone else in this family.

15:05.779 --> 15:09.617
Now this is me messing up again.

15:09.783 --> 15:11.785
[♪♪♪]

15:12.661 --> 15:15.789
You're not messing up, sweetie.
You're not messing up.

15:15.956 --> 15:17.666
It's gonna be okay.

15:18.959 --> 15:21.378
-It'll be fine.
-I can't believe it.

15:21.545 --> 15:23.005
[JESS SOBS]

15:33.641 --> 15:36.352
TRACE: It's not just about the food,
although that's part of it.

15:36.518 --> 15:38.562
Right. It's the whole thing,
the experience.

15:38.729 --> 15:41.607
And every time I push back,
the Waffle King starts making...

15:41.774 --> 15:43.442
...everything about the numbers.

15:43.609 --> 15:45.945
Yields and statistical analysis.

15:46.111 --> 15:47.613
If only life were that simple.

15:47.780 --> 15:48.822
[SCOFFS]

15:48.989 --> 15:51.116
It never is.

15:51.617 --> 15:55.120
Today, I had a meeting
with Terri Ingram.

15:55.287 --> 15:56.455
Why? What's wrong?

15:56.622 --> 15:58.332
Was it about Carrie and Caitlyn?

15:58.499 --> 16:01.460
No. No, um, business.

16:01.627 --> 16:03.504
She wants advice...

16:03.671 --> 16:08.300
...and I'm just having trouble
separating Ms. Marvel from Ms. Ingram.

16:08.467 --> 16:10.094
Yeah. Or Chris from his waffles.

16:10.260 --> 16:11.637
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

16:12.179 --> 16:14.264
Ugh. Know what, it's gonna be fine.

16:14.431 --> 16:18.102
I'm just going to be professional
and do my job.

16:18.268 --> 16:21.397
Yes. And I'm going to try
to get Chris to compromise.

16:21.563 --> 16:23.440
That's good to hear.

16:24.149 --> 16:26.485
-You hungry?
-Yeah. What are you thinking?

16:26.902 --> 16:28.570
Waffles.

16:28.737 --> 16:29.822
-Oh, really?
-Yeah.

16:29.989 --> 16:31.031
That's how it is?

16:31.198 --> 16:32.700
[SQUEALING]

16:32.866 --> 16:35.244
Oh, my gosh. Ah!

16:42.001 --> 16:45.713
My mom is throwing this dinner party
for me on Friday night...

16:45.879 --> 16:47.965
...I was wondering
if you might wanna come.

16:48.132 --> 16:51.176
-Thought you didn't wanna celebrate.
-I don't, it's not a big deal, but--

16:51.343 --> 16:53.178
Of course I'll be there.

16:55.764 --> 16:58.142
So, what would happen
if you didn't go?

16:58.308 --> 17:00.144
To your party?
Didn't you just invite me?

17:00.310 --> 17:02.354
No, to Philly.

17:03.897 --> 17:05.315
Wait, I don't understand.

17:05.482 --> 17:07.693
What would happen
if you just stayed here and worked?

17:07.860 --> 17:10.863
-But you'd be in New York.
-No, I wouldn't. I could stay.

17:11.030 --> 17:14.324
-And do what?
-Look, I don't know, okay?

17:16.243 --> 17:18.871
I don't care. I just....

17:19.830 --> 17:21.957
I don't wanna lose you.

17:22.374 --> 17:25.502
And it wouldn't be forever.
I'd eventually get a paramedic job.

17:25.669 --> 17:27.963
Kevin, you can't do that with your career.

17:28.922 --> 17:31.508
You're a paramedic,
and you're gonna be a great one.

17:31.675 --> 17:33.886
I'm not letting you give that up.
Not for a moment.

17:34.053 --> 17:36.889
What if I don't wanna give you up?
Not even for a moment?

17:37.056 --> 17:39.433
[♪♪♪]

17:39.600 --> 17:42.352
Listen, we'll find a way to make it work.

17:44.313 --> 17:45.689
So I'll go to New York.

17:45.856 --> 17:47.357
And it'll be fun, right?

17:48.233 --> 17:50.652
We can take turns visiting. You'll love Philly.
My brother runs a great restaurant.

17:53.697 --> 17:56.033
And they have the best fries.

17:56.200 --> 17:58.160
Even better than Sally's.

18:03.082 --> 18:07.336
TRACE: I wanna be respectful.
I appreciate everything you're trying to do.

18:07.503 --> 18:09.713
So hopefully we can find
some common ground.

18:09.880 --> 18:10.964
I'd like that.

18:11.131 --> 18:13.926
Now, I'm okay with compromising
on the menus...

18:14.093 --> 18:18.889
...but the Bridge has its own vibe,
you know, its own sound.

18:19.056 --> 18:22.893
I've gone through months of bookings
and cross-referenced them to receipts.

18:23.060 --> 18:25.687
The bands I'm gonna book have
a significantly bigger draw.

18:25.854 --> 18:27.189
[CHUCKLES]

18:27.356 --> 18:30.609
Connecting the music and sales,
especially during lunch...

18:30.776 --> 18:32.653
...is a bit of a stretch, don't you think?

18:32.820 --> 18:36.949
Besides, music is an experience,
it's not a statistic.

18:37.116 --> 18:39.618
We're pretty sure of our numbers.

18:39.785 --> 18:43.497
Okay, let's at least talk
about open-mic night...

18:43.664 --> 18:45.958
...which we created
to support local bands--

18:46.125 --> 18:47.835
No-go. People are coming to listen...

18:48.001 --> 18:50.921
...to their friends and aren't
spending money. This isn't a charity.

18:52.089 --> 18:53.882
Wow. Heh.

18:54.049 --> 18:56.718
You're not even taking in
what I'm saying, are you?

18:57.261 --> 18:59.763
I'm just doing the job
that Mick hired me to do.

18:59.930 --> 19:01.431
But thanks for your input, Trace.

19:01.598 --> 19:05.018
Oh, and we're thinking
of serving waffles.

19:05.185 --> 19:07.187
[♪♪♪]

19:11.692 --> 19:13.193
Hey.

19:15.195 --> 19:16.989
I thought you were done with the book.

19:17.156 --> 19:19.908
[SIGHING]
Not with the fallout.

19:21.535 --> 19:23.412
Mom read it.

19:23.579 --> 19:25.873
Oh, no. Didn't go well?

19:26.039 --> 19:29.793
No. She made it all about her,
even though it's not about her at all.

19:31.962 --> 19:34.131
It's not directly about her.

19:34.298 --> 19:37.342
She managed to make it that way.
And she said that I was wrong.

19:38.635 --> 19:41.680
She said that this isn't the truth.

19:43.849 --> 19:45.559
Maybe it isn't the truth.

19:45.726 --> 19:47.311
Connor....

19:47.769 --> 19:49.313
It is.

19:50.397 --> 19:52.816
Think about it this way.

19:53.150 --> 19:55.110
In court...

19:55.277 --> 19:58.947
...witnesses are never
completely reliable.

19:59.114 --> 20:01.533
And it's not because they're lying... ...it's because we don't
remember memories.

20:04.870 --> 20:08.290
We-- We rebuild them.

20:08.457 --> 20:10.459
[♪♪♪]

20:11.126 --> 20:12.461
So I might be wrong?

20:12.628 --> 20:15.631
No. No, not necessarily.

20:15.797 --> 20:20.385
What we think we remember
may not be exactly--

20:21.261 --> 20:22.804
Exactly what happened.

20:23.513 --> 20:26.058
We don't-- We don't know the full truth.

20:28.101 --> 20:29.519
[SIGHS]

20:31.271 --> 20:33.523
Okay. Um....

20:34.733 --> 20:36.360
What do you remember? Um....

20:42.199 --> 20:45.786
I remember,
Mom wouldn't get out of bed.

20:46.578 --> 20:48.413
For, like, forever.

20:51.375 --> 20:54.169
And then, all of a sudden, she was gone.

20:57.798 --> 21:01.093
I don't really remember the fighting
all that much.

21:04.388 --> 21:05.931
But I do remember...

21:06.098 --> 21:09.476
...hiding in the bushes with Jess.

21:12.562 --> 21:14.064
Like, a lot.

21:18.318 --> 21:19.778
That's what I remember.

21:20.946 --> 21:22.281
[SIGHS]

21:26.451 --> 21:28.120
Come here.

21:39.131 --> 21:41.133
[BAND PLAYING MELLOW MUSIC]

21:48.140 --> 21:50.976
You know, these guys aren't that bad.

21:52.102 --> 21:53.270
Okay, they're really bad.

21:54.021 --> 21:55.480
[ABBY LAUGHS]

21:55.939 --> 21:59.735
So you gonna recommend
Terri do this branding thing?

22:00.193 --> 22:01.903
I don't know.

22:02.487 --> 22:05.407
-What would you do?
-I think she should protect her brand.

22:05.574 --> 22:07.576
Because once you lose control...

22:07.743 --> 22:10.037
...it's all downhill from there.

22:10.454 --> 22:11.997
[SIGHS]

22:18.128 --> 22:19.504
DAVID:
Jess.

22:20.964 --> 22:22.632
Jess.

22:25.010 --> 22:27.804
-Jess, wait, let me help.
-I've got it. I'm fine.

22:27.971 --> 22:29.222
You're not fine. Here.

22:29.389 --> 22:31.600
-Can we talk about this, at least?
-Why?

22:31.767 --> 22:32.976
Because I work here.

22:33.143 --> 22:35.687
You worked here,
but you're free to file unemployment...

22:35.854 --> 22:38.690
...which you'd get if I had paid you,
which I didn't. Sorry.

22:38.857 --> 22:40.942
I'm a horrible boss.
You can leave me now.

22:41.109 --> 22:43.612
-So, what, you're firing me?
-I'm letting you off the hook.

22:43.779 --> 22:47.741
You don't have to feel sorry for me,
or this inn, or the pink towels...

22:47.908 --> 22:51.119
...which are probably still in there
being used as bedding for the termites.

22:51.286 --> 22:54.956
You can go back to being busy
and important.

22:55.123 --> 22:57.084
And remember me fondly
after I'm gone.

22:57.250 --> 22:58.460
You're not dying.

22:58.627 --> 23:01.004
Who knows,
maybe I'll be condemned next.

23:01.171 --> 23:02.964
I'm sorry, I know I'm spiraling.

23:03.131 --> 23:04.758
I just didn't plan for any of this.

23:04.925 --> 23:06.301
Well, neither did I.

23:06.468 --> 23:08.178
But an inn is just an inn.

23:09.096 --> 23:11.389
That's not what's important to me.

23:11.556 --> 23:13.141
It was to me.

23:13.642 --> 23:15.685
I had plans.

23:15.852 --> 23:18.271
Not just for the inn,
but for us and the inn.

23:19.147 --> 23:22.359
You know, cooking classes...

23:22.692 --> 23:24.736
...and themed weekends.

23:24.903 --> 23:26.738
Christmas.

23:27.155 --> 23:30.117
I would have loved
to have done Christmas with you.

23:30.283 --> 23:33.912
We could have had a tree, stockings...

23:34.079 --> 23:36.039
-...and mistletoe.
-Lots of mistletoe.

23:36.206 --> 23:38.083
Mistletoe everywhere.

23:39.126 --> 23:43.797
But knowing my luck,
it'd probably be eaten by termites too.

23:43.964 --> 23:46.216
-Jess.
-Excuse me.

23:46.383 --> 23:48.093
Jess.

23:51.680 --> 23:54.224
-So, what are my odds?
-Hard to say.

23:54.391 --> 23:57.227
No contract is foolproof,
whoever tipped you off...

23:57.394 --> 23:59.187
...to the vulnerabilities has a good eye.

23:59.354 --> 24:00.564
Is it worth pursuing?

24:00.730 --> 24:04.234
I can't say one way or the other,
but if you win...

24:04.401 --> 24:07.320
...and get control back, you'll likely....

24:07.487 --> 24:08.905
Burn a bridge?

24:09.072 --> 24:10.824
Something like that.

24:10.991 --> 24:14.202
The worst of it, Bree wasn't wrong.

24:14.369 --> 24:15.787
I did leave.

24:16.371 --> 24:19.583
But it was so much more complicated
than she made it out to be.

24:19.749 --> 24:22.377
Well, darling,
she doesn't know the whole story.

24:23.461 --> 24:25.422
I've tried to talk to her, Nell.

24:25.589 --> 24:29.342
Now you're going to have to,
and she's gonna have to as well.

24:29.509 --> 24:33.096
Because the past, it isn't sitting still.

24:34.139 --> 24:36.474
-I know.
-Don't forget.

24:36.641 --> 24:42.063
Everyone has their own past
and their own way of seeing it.

24:42.731 --> 24:46.860
And rarely,
rarely is it the same for anyone.

24:48.028 --> 24:51.698
How do I explain what happened?

24:52.949 --> 24:54.868
How I saw things?

24:55.035 --> 24:57.871
Oh, Megan,
you're going to tell her how you felt.

24:58.038 --> 25:00.957
And you're going to tell her
how you feel now.

25:01.499 --> 25:03.210
Because that is the truth.

25:03.376 --> 25:05.462
And that is the only truth.

25:05.629 --> 25:07.631
[♪♪♪]

25:08.131 --> 25:09.674
What if it doesn't help?

25:10.592 --> 25:13.178
Well, then you're going to try again.

25:13.929 --> 25:15.764
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

25:19.476 --> 25:21.436
She just came in.
She's not on your schedule.

25:21.603 --> 25:23.855
-No, I asked her to.
-Celebrating?

25:24.022 --> 25:25.398
Not quite. Heh-heh.

25:25.565 --> 25:27.692
-Hi, thanks for coming.
-Hi. Of course.

25:27.859 --> 25:29.236
Come on in.

25:31.655 --> 25:34.616
So, Terri...

25:35.408 --> 25:37.953
...pretend that we're friends.

25:39.871 --> 25:42.290
Heh. Okay.

25:42.457 --> 25:46.169
Just forget that you're Terri Ingram...

25:46.336 --> 25:49.005
...and I'm Abby O'Brien Winters.

25:49.172 --> 25:52.676
Imagine we are just two women having
a glass of wine in the middle of the day.

25:52.842 --> 25:55.720
-Heh. Works for me.
-Great.

25:55.887 --> 26:00.350
So I heard you're using
a new cleaning product.

26:01.434 --> 26:05.730
I am. It is non-toxic,
all organic and eco-friendly.

26:05.897 --> 26:08.316
Wow. But how do you know that?

26:08.483 --> 26:09.985
It's by the Ms. Marvel brand.

26:10.151 --> 26:12.320
-Oh, I love her blog.
-So do I.

26:12.487 --> 26:13.697
I swear by it.

26:13.863 --> 26:15.991
That's great, but tell me... ...what do you think of her shampoo?

26:18.451 --> 26:21.329
And her body lotion
and her laundry detergent?

26:21.830 --> 26:24.416
-I'm sorry?
-Does Ms. Marvel make those too?

26:25.667 --> 26:28.586
No. Heh.

26:28.753 --> 26:32.007
They will be made by the chemists
at Stewart &amp; Stuart...

26:32.173 --> 26:35.051
...along with all of their other products.

26:35.218 --> 26:37.429
And I won't have a say in it.

26:37.971 --> 26:42.225
Terri, this is a wonderful deal,
financially...

26:42.392 --> 26:45.603
...but, personally...

26:46.646 --> 26:49.274
...I don't think that's why you're doing this.

26:49.441 --> 26:53.278
Ms. Marvel is about quality
and integrity...

26:53.445 --> 26:56.323
...and helping people
who feel helpless.

26:57.198 --> 27:00.493
And that's not
what you're gonna be selling.

27:02.245 --> 27:05.457
And you need to decide
if you're okay with that.

27:08.960 --> 27:10.587
[EXHALES]

27:10.754 --> 27:15.759
So the original factory closed in 1975,
owned by Pennsylvania Steel, sold to--

27:15.925 --> 27:17.761
-Who was it sold to?
-Hopkins Steel...

27:17.927 --> 27:19.888
...who ran the ironworks
for another 10 years.

27:20.055 --> 27:23.767
Right. Giving each company an excuse
not to institute a full cleanup...

27:23.933 --> 27:28.730
...which means that while they argue,
the fish, the plants, the water all suffer.

27:29.647 --> 27:33.985
I mean, I was thinking
we drop <i>Wakefield v. Pascal</i> on them.

27:34.152 --> 27:38.239
Hm. I was thinking <i>Banks v. Lowry,</i>
but I like that. That's good.

27:39.574 --> 27:41.159
Although....

27:41.326 --> 27:42.786
What?

27:43.119 --> 27:44.913
I don't know, what if...?

27:45.080 --> 27:46.664
[♪♪♪]

27:46.831 --> 27:47.999
What if...?

27:48.917 --> 27:54.005
Well, what if we get the feds involved
and go after them on criminal charges?

27:55.090 --> 27:57.258
Oh, do you really think that would fly?

27:57.425 --> 27:59.135
It's worth a try.

28:08.311 --> 28:09.521
[CHUCKLES]

28:09.687 --> 28:12.148
Okay, Connor, this is really smart.

28:12.315 --> 28:14.859
On our end alone,
there'd be thousands of billable hours.

28:15.026 --> 28:17.070
-Right.
-And on their end...

28:17.237 --> 28:19.948
-...bad publicity for both sides.
-Ha.

28:20.365 --> 28:23.034
That is a great place to start.

28:28.706 --> 28:30.291
MICK:
Hey.

28:30.667 --> 28:32.377
Where are you playing tonight?

28:32.544 --> 28:34.712
-Charlottesville.
-Long drive?

28:35.588 --> 28:38.299
Three there, three back,
shouldn't be too bad.

28:39.384 --> 28:41.928
How long do you think
you can keep that up?

28:45.473 --> 28:47.767
-What's this?
-It's our Bridge contract.

28:48.476 --> 28:51.896
If you re-look at section 3A,
fourth line from the top...

28:52.063 --> 28:55.567
...you'll see you don't necessarily
have operational control.

28:55.734 --> 28:57.736
[♪♪♪]

28:57.902 --> 29:00.071
You don't wanna do this.

29:00.238 --> 29:01.990
I don't have a choice, Mick. But you know how it is.

29:04.743 --> 29:06.745
It's just business. [♪♪♪]

29:24.721 --> 29:26.222
I can't believe the inn is gone.

29:26.389 --> 29:30.101
-I can't believe Sarah is moving to Philly.
-I can't believe Danielle is back.

29:30.268 --> 29:32.687
I can't believe
I'm becoming friends with Ms. Marvel.

29:32.854 --> 29:37.275
And I can't believe I wrote about
the entire family in my very first novel.

29:39.152 --> 29:41.821
Yes, I admit it.

29:41.988 --> 29:45.742
And now everybody thinks
I'm the villain. Well, except Simon.

29:45.909 --> 29:48.203
And Dad,
but that's because he hasn't read it yet.

29:48.661 --> 29:51.289
Well, I haven't read it either,
so we're still good.

29:51.456 --> 29:54.042
Assuming I'm a superhero
with super strength.

29:55.293 --> 29:57.712
-Been nice knowing you.
-Heh.

29:57.879 --> 30:01.758
I have nowhere to live or work.

30:01.925 --> 30:04.052
I guess I'll have to stay with Bree forever.

30:04.219 --> 30:07.222
CONNOR: Ha-ha.
-No. No.

30:07.639 --> 30:10.558
Well, hey, at least things
can't get any worse.

30:10.725 --> 30:13.937
Never say never.
Termites strike without warning.

30:14.103 --> 30:16.856
Sarah's brother, Paulie,
has a restaurant in Philly.

30:17.023 --> 30:18.608
Maybe I can go work there.

30:18.775 --> 30:21.194
No, you're a paramedic now.
That is what you do.

30:21.361 --> 30:22.862
You're going to New York.

30:23.029 --> 30:26.199
If you're not happy with your life,
you'll never make her happy either.

30:27.033 --> 30:29.160
That sounded eerily grown-up.

30:29.994 --> 30:33.039
-Have you been channeling Abby?
-Something like that.

30:33.206 --> 30:37.544
-That was good, even for me.
-Yeah, except that means that I...

30:38.044 --> 30:39.254
...am going to New York.

30:39.420 --> 30:41.214
[♪♪♪]

30:52.725 --> 30:54.185
-Hey.
-Hey.

30:54.352 --> 30:56.062
So how's the party planning going?

30:57.146 --> 31:00.567
Oh. It's like all O'Brien affairs,
complicated.

31:01.609 --> 31:04.529
-Why?
-Well, let's see, uh...

31:04.696 --> 31:11.160
...Philly, termites,
Ms. Marvel, a novel, and you.

31:12.829 --> 31:15.957
Me? How did I get involved in all this?

31:17.041 --> 31:19.085
Well, you kind of hired me.

31:20.420 --> 31:21.754
I did, didn't I?

31:21.921 --> 31:24.215
Heh. Yeah.

31:24.716 --> 31:27.135
So Kevin got a job in Philly?

31:27.302 --> 31:31.389
Uh, no, Sarah did.
And Kevin's going to New York.

31:31.556 --> 31:32.849
Oh.

31:33.016 --> 31:35.226
-That's sad.
-I know.

31:35.393 --> 31:38.062
I mean, they really are made
for one another.

31:38.771 --> 31:40.356
Yeah.

31:40.523 --> 31:45.820
I mean, it's hard finding
the right person at the right time, isn't it?

31:45.987 --> 31:47.655
[♪♪♪]

31:47.822 --> 31:52.160
Yeah. Yeah, timing is-- It's everything.

31:52.744 --> 31:55.288
Yeah, it is.

31:56.748 --> 32:01.336
So, uh, how are you and...? Um....

32:02.295 --> 32:05.048
-Davis.
-Davis. Davis.

32:07.008 --> 32:09.177
It wasn't the right time.

32:12.305 --> 32:13.348
Oh.

32:16.184 --> 32:19.520
If you're ready to sign,
we will have the paperwork sent over...

32:19.687 --> 32:22.690
...to Hunter, Drew &amp; Associates.

32:23.983 --> 32:25.234
[EXHALES]

32:26.319 --> 32:30.823
You know, after we talked,
I told Wes what you said, and he agreed.

32:30.990 --> 32:34.369
He also thought
the wine was a nice touch. So did I.

32:34.786 --> 32:37.330
Well, it was probably a Ms. Marvel idea.

32:37.872 --> 32:40.041
Oh, no. I think that was all you.

32:40.833 --> 32:42.251
[CHUCKLES]

32:45.672 --> 32:47.298
You're right.

32:48.675 --> 32:50.802
I can't do this deal.

32:51.719 --> 32:55.139
I wanna help people,
but not at the risk of hurting them.

32:55.306 --> 32:57.892
I can't put my name on a product
I can't fully back.

32:58.059 --> 32:59.727
[♪♪♪]

32:59.894 --> 33:01.187
Wow.

33:01.354 --> 33:06.150
That is very brave, Terri.

33:06.317 --> 33:10.697
I can't believe
I am turning down this much money.

33:10.863 --> 33:16.619
Well, I'm pretty sure you will find
another deal that you can stand behind.

33:17.495 --> 33:18.830
Oh....

33:18.997 --> 33:20.873
-Thank you, Abby.
-Of course.

33:22.208 --> 33:24.335
Do you think
if circumstances were different...

33:24.502 --> 33:26.379
...we could be friends?

33:26.838 --> 33:27.880
[SIGHS]

33:28.047 --> 33:32.760
Terri, I think that we are friends.

33:34.429 --> 33:36.639
You know, I think you're right.

33:36.806 --> 33:39.976
-Heh. Ha-ha.
-Well, good. Let's go.

33:46.649 --> 33:48.276
-Hey.
-Hi.

33:48.443 --> 33:49.902
You look pretty busy.

33:50.069 --> 33:53.406
-Need a hand?
-No, I got this covered.

33:55.825 --> 33:58.453
I was hoping we could talk.

34:00.371 --> 34:01.873
Yeah.

34:02.582 --> 34:04.042
I know.

34:06.294 --> 34:08.046
In your book...

34:09.005 --> 34:12.425
...wasn't as easy
as what you made it seem.

34:14.010 --> 34:15.970
For me, I mean.

34:16.554 --> 34:18.056
Well...

34:18.639 --> 34:21.225
...you didn't have to leave.

34:21.642 --> 34:23.227
I know that. But I couldn't stay either.

34:28.441 --> 34:29.484
Why?

34:30.818 --> 34:34.447
Why couldn't you? You made
a choice to become our mother.

34:34.614 --> 34:38.534
I just don't understand
how you could change your mind.

34:38.701 --> 34:41.287
-I didn't.
-Okay.

34:41.996 --> 34:43.247
[SIGHS]

34:46.209 --> 34:49.378
I wasn't well, Bree, I....

34:51.714 --> 34:55.301
If I had stayed,
I would've brought you all down with me.

34:55.468 --> 34:57.470
[♪♪♪]

35:03.267 --> 35:04.602
[SIGHS]

35:06.270 --> 35:08.731
After I had Jess...

35:09.690 --> 35:11.734
...something just....

35:14.654 --> 35:16.781
I couldn't breathe.

35:18.074 --> 35:21.369
I couldn't get out of bed.

35:23.371 --> 35:25.081
And I couldn't show you.

35:25.248 --> 35:30.837
And couldn't tell you,
and I had no one to talk to.

35:33.923 --> 35:37.552
Your father and I were not
in a good place.

35:38.970 --> 35:43.683
I just wanted you
to have a better life without...

35:46.310 --> 35:48.312
...everything that was going wrong.

35:51.649 --> 35:54.152
So you needed to get help.

35:56.028 --> 35:58.281
But then you got help...

35:59.323 --> 36:01.075
...and you didn't come home.

36:04.120 --> 36:06.956
I mean, if you truly loved us...

36:08.166 --> 36:09.709
...Mom, where were you?

36:12.128 --> 36:16.424
I wanted you to come to New York,
all of you, to live with me, Bree.

36:16.591 --> 36:18.301
But your dad refused.

36:18.467 --> 36:21.429
And, honey, you had your life here.

36:22.638 --> 36:25.850
You had your friends here, you had...

36:26.017 --> 36:27.768
...Gran here.

36:31.189 --> 36:33.691
But all we wanted was you.

36:41.032 --> 36:43.326
[♪♪♪]

36:46.704 --> 36:48.706
BREE: Hey. Um....
-Hey.

36:48.873 --> 36:52.543
-Are you busy?
-For you? Never.

36:53.294 --> 36:56.464
-Um, I need you to talk to Mom.
-Because?

36:56.631 --> 37:00.593
Well, um, she read my manuscript.

37:00.760 --> 37:02.803
And, um, we talked.

37:03.846 --> 37:05.473
And it didn't go well.

37:07.141 --> 37:10.519
Well, then I really
shouldn't get involved, should I?

37:10.978 --> 37:12.438
Well....

37:12.855 --> 37:15.983
I mean, Dad,
you always supported my writing.

37:16.150 --> 37:18.903
-Told me my words matter.
-Yes.

37:19.070 --> 37:21.364
That I write the truth.

37:22.615 --> 37:23.866
So....

37:24.992 --> 37:26.661
Okay.

37:26.827 --> 37:29.038
Let me see what I can do.

37:29.413 --> 37:30.998
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

37:31.165 --> 37:32.875
Good luck.

37:44.470 --> 37:46.472
[♪♪♪]

37:48.349 --> 37:50.184
What is going on?

37:50.351 --> 37:52.687
Almost there, keep them closed.

37:52.853 --> 37:54.605
Okay.

37:55.273 --> 37:57.483
Okay, you can open.

38:03.781 --> 38:06.951
What in the world?

38:07.118 --> 38:10.413
-Merry Christmas.
-Ah. Ah.

38:14.667 --> 38:16.168
Oh....

38:21.924 --> 38:23.467
[CHUCKLES]

38:24.385 --> 38:26.304
I'm not attached to places.

38:26.804 --> 38:29.473
But I know how important this is for you.

38:29.640 --> 38:33.227
If you wanna have Christmas at the inn,
we'll have Christmas at the inn.

38:33.811 --> 38:38.774
And next Christmas will be
just as special, no matter where we are.

38:39.525 --> 38:42.361
-Because we'll be together.
-Oh....

38:42.528 --> 38:44.822
Oh, wait, wait, wait.

38:46.657 --> 38:47.867
-Mistletoe.
-Ha-ha-ha.

38:49.118 --> 38:51.162
I love you.

38:51.996 --> 38:53.831
I-- I mean...

38:54.582 --> 38:56.459
...sort of.

38:56.876 --> 38:58.544
Not really.

38:58.711 --> 39:00.629
Guys should say it first.

39:00.796 --> 39:03.007
You should open your card.

39:06.427 --> 39:09.096
"I love you. Love, David."

39:09.847 --> 39:13.267
Okay, so you did say it first.
Twice, actually.

39:14.602 --> 39:15.811
I love you, Jess.

39:16.354 --> 39:18.314
I love you too.

39:21.734 --> 39:24.028
What's in the stockings?

39:24.195 --> 39:26.906
-Uh, probably termites.
-Ugh....

39:27.865 --> 39:29.408
Thank you.

39:33.829 --> 39:35.831
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

39:41.379 --> 39:42.838
Hey.

39:43.631 --> 39:45.841
You hiding on purpose?

39:46.550 --> 39:48.427
You didn't see me.

39:51.180 --> 39:53.140
Everybody.

39:53.307 --> 39:55.226
[♪♪♪]

39:56.560 --> 40:00.648
Today, we celebrate the graduation
of our eldest son.

40:02.733 --> 40:06.153
And I just wanna let you all know
how grateful I am to be here...

40:06.320 --> 40:07.488
...with all of you.

40:09.573 --> 40:13.119
To share this family milestone.

40:19.458 --> 40:20.626
[DOOR OPENS]

40:26.841 --> 40:29.593
-To Kevin.
MICK: To Kevin.

40:49.155 --> 40:50.489
Hey.

40:53.576 --> 40:56.036
So, um...

40:56.454 --> 40:58.706
...did you talk to Mom?

41:03.043 --> 41:04.628
You can't publish this.

41:05.963 --> 41:07.506
Why?

41:07.840 --> 41:10.926
-It's the truth.
-No, it's your truth. Not the family's.

41:11.802 --> 41:13.929
-What?
-Bree...

41:14.096 --> 41:16.182
...we all did the best we could.

41:16.348 --> 41:19.768
There's no guidebook
on how to parent...

41:19.935 --> 41:23.022
...or how to handle a marriage
or family that's falling apart.

41:23.189 --> 41:24.732
I know that.

41:25.149 --> 41:26.233
That's why I wrote this.

41:26.400 --> 41:28.652
I wanted to try to understand
what happened. Yeah, but instead,
you opened a gaping wound...

41:31.238 --> 41:34.074
...and decided to share it
with the world.

41:35.034 --> 41:37.036
[♪♪♪]

41:38.412 --> 41:39.622
I--

41:41.665 --> 41:43.542
I don't understand you.

42:02.061 --> 42:04.063
[♪♪♪]

44:01.764 --> 44:03.474
NARRATOR:
<i>Next time on </i>Chesapeake Shores:

44:03.641 --> 44:06.310
You're Bree O'Brien.
It is such a pleasure to meet you.

44:06.477 --> 44:07.770
-I'm--
-Caroline.

44:07.936 --> 44:10.314
BOTH: Simon.
-She wants to get back together.

44:10.481 --> 44:12.483
-Don't know if I can trust her.
-Trust yourself.

44:12.650 --> 44:17.404
-Tour's been extended six months.
-This is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity.

44:17.571 --> 44:20.366
I'm gonna give you advice.
If you really care about something...
